        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>San Francisco</placeName>
                <date>April 15. 1854</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Friend — </p>
            <p>I have recd the Books with Steamer<lb/> before last, and I hope by next time<lb/> to
                be able to send you some money.<lb/> I have sold of the books thus far<lb/> 2 Bibles
                at $9, 3 at $12—10 <persName>D.</persName> letters.<lb/> 2 German P. Books &amp; 1
                set Prayer<lb/> Books at $31. I think you done wrong<lb/> incurring the expense of
                sending<lb/> the books across the <placeName>Isthmus</placeName>, as people<lb/>
                generally find it too much to pay<lb/> 50 cts. additional to every pound. I<lb/>
                think I have written to you to make<lb/> a notice in the Occident that you have<lb/>
                sent me out such books, which if you had<lb/> it done, would have assisted to
                have<lb/> all the books sold till now; as there are<lb/> no doubt people which are
                unaware that<lb/> I have these books to sell, who would want<lb/> them &amp; might
                find it out through the Occident.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Now I will at once proceed to give you<lb/> some News; if I can
                think or know<lb/> of any, as there are but very little of any interest</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>to you at present worthy almost of mention.<lb/> Today is the <date>third day of
                    Pesach</date>, and<lb/> so far the synagogues were well attended,<lb/> and many
                families, most of them keep it<lb/> &amp; have Mazoes; to give you a proof of<lb/>
                the general observance, I might only tell<lb/> you that one man has sold $160
                worth<lb/> of horse radish necessary to the Ceder<lb/> ceremony.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The Committee appointed to give out<lb/> proposals &amp;c have not
                as yet determined<lb/> their labors; but it is decided that the<lb/> cost of the
                building alone would not exceed<lb/> the amt. of $20.00—; for this money a<lb/> fair
                building<lb/> can be put up.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I would like you to speak in some laudable<lb/> terms of the “<hi
                    rend="underline">Young Men's Debating<lb/> Society</hi>” in the next number of
                the Occi-<lb/>-dent. This Society is only about 6 weeks<lb/> in existence &amp; has
                already between 30 &amp;<lb/> 40 members; the object of the Society is<lb/> for the
                improvement in debating in discussing various<lb/> kinds of questions. The Society
                is composed<lb/> of young men of our persuasion, but the<lb/> zeal, energy &amp;
                rivalry, and the interest taken<lb/> &amp; manifested by the young men does
                really<lb/> honor and reflect great credit upon the Jewish<lb/> young men in
                    <placeName>San Francisco</placeName>. <persName>Mr.<lb/> S. C. Labatt</persName>
                is President.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Please give my kind regards to <persName>Mr. M. Allen</persName></p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>and please mention to him that I<lb/> have recd his letter &amp; shall answer it<lb/>
                soon.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr. and Mrs. Roggenburger</persName> request me<lb/> to
                give their kind regards to you,<lb/> &amp; trusting this may find<lb/> you in the
                enjoyment of<lb/> good health</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">I remain</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">Yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">(Signed) <persName role="author">Cauffman H. Meyer</persName></p>
            <p>Excuse my bad writing as I</p>
            <p>have written this in great haste.</p>
